# Module 05 — Observability

> The meta-layer: the harness treats itself as a measurable object. Without this layer, every other layer's effect is guesswork.

## Essence

You cannot improve what you can't see.

## Hard Constraints

### 1. Every agent action is traceable

- One task = one trace. Every tool call / subagent dispatch / retry = one span
- Minimum per span: `input`, `output`, `cost`, `latency`, `retry_count`
- Minimum viable: JSONL locally. Production: OpenTelemetry / LangSmith / Langfuse
- **No trace = no debugging.** "It got worse" without traces is unfalsifiable

On Cursor, the `stop` hook logs every stop event to `.cursor-harness/stop-log.jsonl` via `scripts/stop-logger.sh`. Even though Cursor's Stop hook can't block, it can observe — and observation is the foundation of this module.

### 2. Drift monitoring — background fitness function

- Maintain a **golden task set**: 10–20 representative tasks the harness should handle well
- On every meaningful change (rule edit, hook swap), replay the golden set
- Record scores as a time series
- **Score drops > X%** = regression → investigate before shipping

### 3. Meta-evaluation — the harness has its own benchmark

- 7 dimensions × golden tasks = harness benchmark
- Corresponds to METR's *elicitation gap*: same model, different harness → different score
- Every rule change → re-run → commit the score alongside the change
- Otherwise "was that edit a regression or improvement" is a guess

### 4. Measure process, not just output

Output metrics (success rate, test pass rate) miss:
- Thrashing (many edits, eventually succeeds — slow burn)
- Over-grep (reading the same file five times)
- Context exhaustion (hits 95% budget and degrades)

These are the signals that catch "getting dumb" before success rate drops.

### 5. Cost and latency are first-class

Token cost per task. Wall clock per task. A task solved in 30s at $0.05 vs 30min at $5 is the same "success" in a binary metric — but a completely different harness quality.

## Why this is the cure for "long sessions get dumb"

Cross-module pathology:
- Module 01 (context) may lack summarization checkpoints
- Module 04 (memory) may load polluted / stale entries every turn
- **Module 05: without traces, you can't tell which is the culprit**

The fix order has to start here. Patch what you can see.

## cursor-harness deliverables

- [x] `scripts/stop-logger.sh` — appends stop events to `.cursor-harness/stop-log.jsonl`
- [ ] `evals/golden/` — golden task set (10–20 prompts + expected criteria)
- [ ] `scripts/bench-harness.mjs` — golden task runner + scorer
- [ ] Post-change workflow: edit rule → run bench → diff scores → commit with result

## When to apply

- About to change a rule — run the bench first, then after, compare
- User reports "it's dumber lately" — pull traces, not guesses
- Adding a new sensor → it should emit a metric, not just a warning line
- Debugging "why did it use 50k tokens for a 3-file change" — look at the trace

## Anti-patterns

- "I improved the rule, feels better" — with no bench, feels = survivorship bias
- Logging everything but measuring nothing
- Looking only at success rate — masks slow-and-expensive successes
- Running the bench once and never again — drift is a time series

